sh <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’). In Bedfordshire it probably denoted a settlement on a bend (Old English <i>byge</i> + genitive singular <i>-es</i> + <i>tūn</i>). The hamlet stands on a marked bend of the river Yvel. In Cheshire it is named from a rock, below which trading took place (Old English <i>byge</i> ‘commerce’ + Old English <i>stān</i> ‘stone’). The reference is to a prominent crag where the remains of Beeston Castle stand. Compare   Beaston   and   Beeson  .","occasionally a topographic name for someone who lived in that part of a village known in Middle English as <i>bi este toun</i> ‘(place) at the east (end) of the village’."],"variants":[{"name":"Beston","meanings":["English: variant of   Beeston   and   Beaston  ."]},{"name":"Beeson","meanings":["English: variant of   Beeston  , a habitational name from a place called Beeston. The spelling reflects the local pronunciation of the Nottinghamshire placename, although this form is now quite widespread in England."]},{"name":"Beaston","meanings":["English: variant of   Beeston   (the more common form of the surname in England), a habitational name from any of various places called Beeston."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":12,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When John Beeston was born in 1370, in Runcorn, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Lord William Beeston, was 28 and his mother, Isabel Stoke, was 29. He married Margaret Hulgreve in